# Feature Selection Method - Wrapper method - Backward Stepwise Elimination - Dropping independent variables (features) one at
# a time, starting with the variable with the highest p-value, and rerun the model and repeat, until we are left with 
#v ariables with < 0.05 p-values. This process is used to optimize the effectiveness of the model since it will include only 
# the most signifcant variables and drop the least significant variables.

# Start with Item8 as it has the highest p-value. Then checking model again.
df = df.drop(columns=['Item8'])

# import variance_inflation_factor to run VIF to remove multicollinearity from the model.
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor


# the independent variables set
X = df[['Children', 'MonthlyCharge', 'Bandwidth_GB_Year', 'Churn_Yes', 'Multiple_Yes', 'OnlineSecurity_Yes', 
        'OnlineBackup_Yes', 'DeviceProtection_Yes', 'TechSupport_Yes', 'StreamingTV_Yes', 'StreamingMovies_Yes', 
        'InternetService_DSL', 'InternetService_Fiber Optic', 'InternetService_None']]

# VIF dataframe
vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
vif_data["feature"] = X.columns

# calculating VIF for each feature a.k.a. independent variables / predictors for multicollinearity. Independent varirables with
# a variance inflation factor of > 10 have a strong relationship to another independent variable. The concept is that when
# one independent variable influences another in a similar way, you would only need one of the variables as the results will be
# redundant with both variables remaining in the dataset.
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i)
for i in range(len(X.columns))]

print(vif_data)
